---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
import CIICalculator from '../components/CIICalculator.jsx';
---

<Layout 
    title="IMO Ship CII Calculator | Carbon Intensity Indicator | BrightMariner"
    description="Calculate your vessel's IMO Operational Carbon Intensity Indicator (CII) rating, required reduction factors, and ratings boundaries. Get printable PDF reports and view EEDI/EEXI FAQs."
>
    <!-- Structured Data Schemas for SEO -->
    <script type="application/ld+json" is:inline>
        {
            "@context": "https://schema.org",
            "@graph": [
                {
                    "@type": "WebApplication",
                    "@id": "https://brightmariner.com/cii-calculator/#webapp",
                    "url": "https://brightmariner.com/cii-calculator/",
                    "name": "IMO Ship CII Calculator",
                    "applicationCategory": "BusinessApplication",
                    "operatingSystem": "All",
                    "browserRequirements": "Requires JavaScript. Requires HTML5.",
                    "description": "An interactive tool to calculate a vessel's attained and required Carbon Intensity Indicator (CII) operational rating and rating boundaries in accordance with IMO MEPC.354(78) guidelines.",
                    "offers": {
                        "@type": "Offer",
                        "price": "0.00",
                        "priceCurrency": "USD"
                    }
                },
                {
                    "@type": "FAQPage",
                    "@id": "https://brightmariner.com/cii-calculator/#faq",
                    "mainEntity": [
                        {
                            "@type": "Question",
                            "name": "What is EEXI and EEDI?",
                            "acceptedAnswer": {
                                "@type": "Answer",
                                "text": "EEDI (Energy Efficiency Design Index) is a mandatory technical design standard for new ships built after 2013. EEXI (Energy Efficiency Existing Ship Index) is the equivalent index for existing ships. Both calculate the theoretical design efficiency based on installed power, speed, capacity, and fuel factors."
                            }
                        },
                        {
                            "@type": "Question",
                            "name": "What is EEXI in shipping?",
                            "acceptedAnswer": {
                                "@type": "Answer",
                                "text": "EEXI (Energy Efficiency Existing Ship Index) is a one-time technical measure introduced by the IMO under MARPOL Annex VI to evaluate the design energy efficiency of existing ships over 400 GT. It requires existing vessels to meet a specific baseline efficiency comparable to newer EEDI-compliant vessels."
                            }
                        },
                        {
                            "@type": "Question",
                            "name": "What is the difference between EEXI and CII?",
                            "acceptedAnswer": {
                                "@type": "Answer",
                                "text": "EEXI is a design/technical index calculated once. It measures how the ship is built (its theoretical efficiency). CII (Carbon Intensity Indicator) is an operational measure calculated annually based on actual fuel consumed and distance sailed. It measures how the ship is operated in practice."
                            }
                        },
                        {
                            "@type": "Question",
                            "name": "How to calculate EEXI for ships?",
                            "acceptedAnswer": {
                                "@type": "Answer",
                                "text": "EEXI is calculated by dividing the CO₂ emissions from the vessel's propulsion and auxiliary systems by the product of the ship's capacity (DWT or GT) and its reference speed: EEXI = (CO₂ Emissions from Main + Aux Engines) / (Capacity × Reference Speed)."
                            }
                        },
                        {
                            "@type": "Question",
                            "name": "What is the difference between EEOI and EEDI?",
                            "acceptedAnswer": {
                                "@type": "Answer",
                                "text": "EEDI (Energy Efficiency Design Index) is a design index for new ships (theoretical efficiency). EEOI (Energy Efficiency Operational Indicator) is an operational monitoring tool that measures actual CO₂ emissions per actual cargo carried per nautical mile during real voyages."
                            }
                        },
                        {
                            "@type": "Question",
                            "name": "What are the 4 major components of EDI?",
                            "acceptedAnswer": {
                                "@type": "Answer",
                                "text": "In shipping and logistics, EDI (Electronic Data Interchange) comprises four core components: 1. Standard Document Format (e.g., UN/EDIFACT), 2. Translation Software, 3. Transmission/Communication Network (AS2, SFTP, VANs), and 4. Trading Partners."
                            }
                        },
                        {
                            "@type": "Question",
                            "name": "What is the carbon intensity indicator?",
                            "acceptedAnswer": {
                                "@type": "Answer",
                                "text": "The Carbon Intensity Indicator (CII) is an operational rating system introduced by the IMO under MARPOL Annex VI. It rates ships (5,000 GT and above) annually on a scale from A (major superior) to E (inferior) based on actual operational carbon emissions per transport capacity and distance."
                            }
                        },
                        {
                            "@type": "Question",
                            "name": "How do you measure carbon intensity?",
                            "acceptedAnswer": {
                                "@type": "Answer",
                                "text": "Operational carbon intensity is measured by dividing the ship's annual CO₂ emissions (calculated from actual fuel consumed multiplied by fuel-specific conversion factors) by its annual transport work (vessel capacity in DWT or GT multiplied by total distance sailed in nautical miles)."
                            }
                        },
                        {
                            "@type": "Question",
                            "name": "What is 3% CO2 in ppm?",
                            "acceptedAnswer": {
                                "@type": "Answer",
                                "text": "Percent concentration is measured in parts per hundred. Since 1% is equal to 10,000 parts per million (ppm), a concentration of 3% CO₂ is equal to 30,000 ppm."
                            }
                        },
                        {
                            "@type": "Question",
                            "name": "What is a good CI score?",
                            "acceptedAnswer": {
                                "@type": "Answer",
                                "text": "Under the IMO CII framework, a 'good' rating is an A or B rating (major or minor superior performance). A rating of C is acceptable (moderate). Ratings of D (for three consecutive years) or E require corrective action plans in the vessel's SEEMP."
                            }
                        },
                        {
                            "@type": "Question",
                            "name": "What are the 4 pillars of CII?",
                            "acceptedAnswer": {
                                "@type": "Answer",
                                "text": "The management of CII is structured around 4 pillars: 1. Planning (SEEMP baselines & targets), 2. Implementation/Operation (speed/route planning), 3. Monitoring & Reporting (fuel/voyage data), and 4. Self-Evaluation/Corrective Action."
                            }
                        },
                        {
                            "@type": "Question",
                            "name": "What is FOB C&F and CIF?",
                            "acceptedAnswer": {
                                "@type": "Answer",
                                "text": "These are Incoterms: FOB (Free on Board) means the buyer bears costs/risks from the loading port. C&F (Cost and Freight) means the seller pays freight to the destination port, but risks transfer at loading. CIF (Cost, Insurance, and Freight) is same as C&F, plus seller-procured marine insurance."
                            }
                        }
                     ]
                 }
             ]
         }
     </script>
    <section class="relative pt-12 pb-24 overflow-hidden mesh-gradient">
        <div class="max-w-(--page-width) mx-auto px-6 lg:px-8 relative z-10">
            <header class="text-center mb-12">
                <div class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 px-3 py-1 bg-canvas border border-hairline rounded-full mb-4">
                    <span class="text-[10px] font-mono uppercase tracking-widest text-mute">IMO Regulations Compliance</span>
                    <span class="text-xs font-medium text-ink">Version 2.0</span>
                </div>
                <h1 class="text-4xl md:text-6xl font-semibold tracking-tighter text-ink mb-4">
                    Ship Carbon Intensity Indicator (CII) Calculator
                </h1>
                <p class="text-lg text-body max-w-2xl mx-auto leading-relaxed">
                    Analyze your vessel's carbon intensity rating. Estimate voyage emissions, model weather resistance, and optimize operational speed profiles.
                </p>
            </header>

            <!-- Main Interactive Calculator Container -->
            <div class="mt-8">
                <CIICalculator client:load />
            </div>
        </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Detailed content details footer section -->
    <section class="border-t border-hairline bg-canvas py-16 px-6 lg:px-8">
        <div class="max-w-(--page-width) mx-auto grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-3 gap-12">
            <div>
                <h3 class="font-semibold text-ink mb-3">About the CII Calculator</h3>
                <p class="text-sm text-body leading-relaxed">
                    This interactive tool lets shipowners and operators evaluate their vessel's operational energy efficiency based on the International Maritime Organization (IMO) MARPOL Annex VI regulations. By inputting details about sea conditions, operational speed, draft, and fuel consumption, you can simulate and optimize your annual operational Carbon Intensity Indicator (CII).
                </p>
            </div>
            <div>
                <h3 class="font-semibold text-ink mb-3">How CII is Calculated</h3>
                <p class="text-sm text-body leading-relaxed">
                    The attained CII represents the carbon emissions of the ship per cargo capacity (usually Deadweight Tonnage, DWT) and nautical mile. This calculator uses the annual fuel consumption, distance sailed, and vessel capacity to determine the attained and required CII ratings in accordance with the IMO G1-G4 guidelines.
                </p>
            </div>
            <div>
                <h3 class="font-semibold text-ink mb-3">Compliance Requirements</h3>
                <p class="text-sm text-body leading-relaxed">
                    Ships are rated from A (major superior) to E (inferior). A rating of C or better is required. Vessels receiving a D rating for three consecutive years, or an E rating in a single year, must develop a corrective action plan as part of their Ship Energy Efficiency Management Plan (SEEMP) Part III.
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </section>

    <!-- FAQ Section -->
    <section class="border-t border-hairline bg-canvas-soft py-16 px-6 lg:px-8">
        <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto">
            <h2 class="text-3xl font-semibold tracking-tighter text-ink mb-8 text-center">
                Frequently Asked Questions
            </h2>
            <div class="space-y-4">
                <details class="group bg-canvas border border-hairline rounded-xl p-5 shadow-xs [&_summary::-webkit-details-marker]:hidden">
                    <summary class="flex justify-between items-center font-semibold text-ink cursor-pointer list-none">
                        <span>What is EEXI and EEDI?</span>
                        <span class="transition-transform group-open:rotate-180">
                            <svg class="w-5 h-5 text-mute" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path></svg>
                        </span>
                    </summary>
                    <p class="text-sm text-body leading-relaxed mt-3 pt-3 border-t border-hairline">
                        <strong>EEDI (Energy Efficiency Design Index)</strong> is a design standard for <em>new ships</em> built after 2013, requiring a minimum energy efficiency level per capacity-mile.
                        <br/><br/>
                        <strong>EEXI (Energy Efficiency Existing Ship Index)</strong> is the design standard for <em>existing ships</em> (built before 2013 or not subject to EEDI). Both indexes calculate the theoretical design efficiency based on installed power, speed, capacity, and fuel factors.
                    </p>
                </details>

                <details class="group bg-canvas border border-hairline rounded-xl p-5 shadow-xs [&_summary::-webkit-details-marker]:hidden">
                    <summary class="flex justify-between items-center font-semibold text-ink cursor-pointer list-none">
                        <span>What is EEXI in shipping?</span>
                        <span class="transition-transform group-open:rotate-180">
                            <svg class="w-5 h-5 text-mute" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path></svg>
                        </span>
                    </summary>
                    <p class="text-sm text-body leading-relaxed mt-3 pt-3 border-t border-hairline">
                        <strong>EEXI (Energy Efficiency Existing Ship Index)</strong> is a one-time technical measure introduced by the IMO under MARPOL Annex VI to evaluate the design energy efficiency of existing ships over 400 GT. It requires existing vessels to meet a specific baseline efficiency comparable to newer EEDI-compliant vessels.
                    </p>
                </details>

                <details class="group bg-canvas border border-hairline rounded-xl p-5 shadow-xs [&_summary::-webkit-details-marker]:hidden">
                    <summary class="flex justify-between items-center font-semibold text-ink cursor-pointer list-none">
                        <span>What is the difference between EEXI and CII?</span>
                        <span class="transition-transform group-open:rotate-180">
                            <svg class="w-5 h-5 text-mute" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path></svg>
                        </span>
                    </summary>
                    <p class="text-sm text-body leading-relaxed mt-3 pt-3 border-t border-hairline">
                        <strong>EEXI</strong> is a <strong>design/technical index</strong> calculated once. It measures how the ship is <em>built</em> (its theoretical efficiency).
                        <br/><br/>
                        <strong>CII (Carbon Intensity Indicator)</strong> is an <strong>operational measure</strong> calculated <em>annually</em> based on actual fuel consumed and distance sailed. It measures how the ship is <em>operated</em> in practice.
                    </p>
                </details>

                <details class="group bg-canvas border border-hairline rounded-xl p-5 shadow-xs [&_summary::-webkit-details-marker]:hidden">
                    <summary class="flex justify-between items-center font-semibold text-ink cursor-pointer list-none">
                        <span>How to calculate EEXI for ships?</span>
                        <span class="transition-transform group-open:rotate-180">
                            <svg class="w-5 h-5 text-mute" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path></svg>
                        </span>
                    </summary>
                    <p class="text-sm text-body leading-relaxed mt-3 pt-3 border-t border-hairline">
                        EEXI is calculated by dividing the CO₂ emissions from the vessel's propulsion and auxiliary systems by the product of the ship's capacity (DWT or GT) and its reference speed:
                        <br/><br/>
                        <code class="block bg-canvas-soft-2 p-2 rounded text-xs font-mono">EEXI = (CO₂ Emissions from Main + Aux Engines) / (Capacity × Reference Speed)</code>
                        <br/>
                        This represents the theoretical grams of CO₂ emitted per capacity-mile under reference load conditions.
                    </p>
                </details>

                <details class="group bg-canvas border border-hairline rounded-xl p-5 shadow-xs [&_summary::-webkit-details-marker]:hidden">
                    <summary class="flex justify-between items-center font-semibold text-ink cursor-pointer list-none">
                        <span>What is the difference between EEOI and EEDI?</span>
                        <span class="transition-transform group-open:rotate-180">
                            <svg class="w-5 h-5 text-mute" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path></svg>
                        </span>
                    </summary>
                    <p class="text-sm text-body leading-relaxed mt-3 pt-3 border-t border-hairline">
                        <strong>EEDI (Energy Efficiency Design Index)</strong> is a design index for <em>new ships</em> (theoretical efficiency under standard conditions).
                        <br/><br/>
                        <strong>EEOI (Energy Efficiency Operational Indicator)</strong> is an operational monitoring tool that measures actual CO₂ emissions per actual cargo carried per nautical mile during real voyages. EEOI uses actual cargo weight, whereas EEDI (and CII) uses maximum ship capacity (DWT/GT).
                    </p>
                </details>

                <details class="group bg-canvas border border-hairline rounded-xl p-5 shadow-xs [&_summary::-webkit-details-marker]:hidden">
                    <summary class="flex justify-between items-center font-semibold text-ink cursor-pointer list-none">
                        <span>What are the 4 major components of EDI?</span>
                        <span class="transition-transform group-open:rotate-180">
                            <svg class="w-5 h-5 text-mute" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path></svg>
                        </span>
                    </summary>
                    <p class="text-sm text-body leading-relaxed mt-3 pt-3 border-t border-hairline">
                        In shipping and logistics, <strong>EDI (Electronic Data Interchange)</strong> comprises four core components:
                        <br/><br/>
                        1. <strong>Standard Document Format</strong>: Standardized document layouts (e.g., UN/EDIFACT or ANSI X12) that replace paper.
                        <br/>
                        2. <strong>Translation Software</strong>: Converts internal database applications into standard EDI formats for transmission.
                        <br/>
                        3. <strong>Transmission / Communication Network</strong>: Protocols and routes used to send documents (like SFTP, AS2, or Value-Added Networks).
                        <br/>
                        4. <strong>Trading Partners</strong>: The organizations (e.g., shippers, carriers, ports) exchanging the data.
                        <br/><br/>
                        <em>(Note: In ship design contexts, EEDI calculation components focus on engine power, specific fuel consumption, carbon factor, and capacity/speed.)</em>
                    </p>
                </details>

                <details class="group bg-canvas border border-hairline rounded-xl p-5 shadow-xs [&_summary::-webkit-details-marker]:hidden">
                    <summary class="flex justify-between items-center font-semibold text-ink cursor-pointer list-none">
                        <span>What is the carbon intensity indicator?</span>
                        <span class="transition-transform group-open:rotate-180">
                            <svg class="w-5 h-5 text-mute" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path></svg>
                        </span>
                    </summary>
                    <p class="text-sm text-body leading-relaxed mt-3 pt-3 border-t border-hairline">
                        The <strong>Carbon Intensity Indicator (CII)</strong> is an operational rating system introduced by the IMO under MARPOL Annex VI. It rates ships (5,000 GT and above) annually on a scale from A (major superior) to E (inferior) based on their actual operational carbon emissions per transport capacity and distance.
                    </p>
                </details>

                <details class="group bg-canvas border border-hairline rounded-xl p-5 shadow-xs [&_summary::-webkit-details-marker]:hidden">
                    <summary class="flex justify-between items-center font-semibold text-ink cursor-pointer list-none">
                        <span>How do you measure carbon intensity?</span>
                        <span class="transition-transform group-open:rotate-180">
                            <svg class="w-5 h-5 text-mute" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path></svg>
                        </span>
                    </summary>
                    <p class="text-sm text-body leading-relaxed mt-3 pt-3 border-t border-hairline">
                        Operational carbon intensity is measured by dividing the ship's annual CO₂ emissions (calculated from actual fuel consumed multiplied by fuel-specific conversion factors) by its annual transport work (vessel capacity in DWT or GT multiplied by total distance sailed in nautical miles).
                    </p>
                </details>

                <details class="group bg-canvas border border-hairline rounded-xl p-5 shadow-xs [&_summary::-webkit-details-marker]:hidden">
                    <summary class="flex justify-between items-center font-semibold text-ink cursor-pointer list-none">
                        <span>What is 3% CO2 in ppm?</span>
                        <span class="transition-transform group-open:rotate-180">
                            <svg class="w-5 h-5 text-mute" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path></svg>
                        </span>
                    </summary>
                    <p class="text-sm text-body leading-relaxed mt-3 pt-3 border-t border-hairline">
                        Percent concentration is measured in parts per hundred. Since 1% is equal to 10,000 parts per million (ppm), a concentration of <strong>3% CO₂ is equal to 30,000 ppm</strong>.
                    </p>
                </details>

                <details class="group bg-canvas border border-hairline rounded-xl p-5 shadow-xs [&_summary::-webkit-details-marker]:hidden">
                    <summary class="flex justify-between items-center font-semibold text-ink cursor-pointer list-none">
                        <span>What is a good CI score?</span>
                        <span class="transition-transform group-open:rotate-180">
                            <svg class="w-5 h-5 text-mute" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path></svg>
                        </span>
                    </summary>
                    <p class="text-sm text-body leading-relaxed mt-3 pt-3 border-t border-hairline">
                        Under the IMO CII framework, a "good" rating is an <strong>A or B rating</strong> (major or minor superior energy efficiency performance). A rating of <strong>C</strong> is acceptable (moderate). Ratings of <strong>D</strong> (for three consecutive years) or <strong>E</strong> require corrective action plans in the vessel's SEEMP.
                    </p>
                </details>

                <details class="group bg-canvas border border-hairline rounded-xl p-5 shadow-xs [&_summary::-webkit-details-marker]:hidden">
                    <summary class="flex justify-between items-center font-semibold text-ink cursor-pointer list-none">
                        <span>What are the 4 pillars of CII?</span>
                        <span class="transition-transform group-open:rotate-180">
                            <svg class="w-5 h-5 text-mute" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path></svg>
                        </span>
                    </summary>
                    <p class="text-sm text-body leading-relaxed mt-3 pt-3 border-t border-hairline">
                        The management and compliance of a ship's Carbon Intensity Indicator (CII) are structured around the 4 pillars of the SEEMP (Ship Energy Efficiency Management Plan):
                        <br/><br/>
                        1. <strong>Planning</strong>: Establishing baselines, target CII ratings, and detailed operational measures to meet target guidelines.
                        <br/>
                        2. <strong>Implementation / Operation</strong>: Putting planned actions (e.g., speed optimization, route planning, trim optimization) into daily practice.
                        <br/>
                        3. <strong>Monitoring & Reporting</strong>: Collecting daily fuel consumption and voyage data under the IMO Data Collection System (DCS).
                        <br/>
                        4. <strong>Self-Evaluation & Corrective Action</strong>: Auditing annual results and developing corrective plans if the vessel falls below a 'C' rating.
                    </p>
                </details>

                <details class="group bg-canvas border border-hairline rounded-xl p-5 shadow-xs [&_summary::-webkit-details-marker]:hidden">
                    <summary class="flex justify-between items-center font-semibold text-ink cursor-pointer list-none">
                        <span>What is FOB C&F and CIF?</span>
                        <span class="transition-transform group-open:rotate-180">
                            <svg class="w-5 h-5 text-mute" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path></svg>
                        </span>
                    </summary>
                    <p class="text-sm text-body leading-relaxed mt-3 pt-3 border-t border-hairline">
                        These are standard Incoterms (International Commercial Terms) defining who pays for and bears the risk of shipping goods:
                        <br/><br/>
                        - <strong>FOB (Free on Board)</strong>: The seller delivers goods on board the buyer's nominated vessel. The buyer bears all costs and risks from the loading port to destination.
                        <br/>
                        - <strong>C&F / CFR (Cost and Freight)</strong>: The seller pays for transport/freight to the destination port, but risks transfer to the buyer once the goods are loaded.
                        <br/>
                        - <strong>CIF (Cost, Insurance, and Freight)</strong>: The same as C&F, but the seller must also pay for marine insurance to protect the goods during transit.
                    </p>
                </details>
            </div>
        </div>
    </section>
</Layout>
